Here are the complete structured notes for Episode 18 / Core CSS Concept: CSS Size Units in Depth from Love Babbar's web development course.In this session, the discussion shifts to sizing architectures in CSS. Sizing units control how dimensions scale across different hardware matrices and layout breakpoints.1. Sizing Unit ClassificationsCSS segregates sizing values into two fundamental categories:Absolute Units: Fixed structural values that remain completely static regardless of display scale, zooming tiers, or parent container modifications.  Relative Units: Dynamic, scalable values tied linearly to an baseline tracking index, such as a root font-size, a parent container wrapper, or the browser window dimensions.  2. Absolute Sizing: Pixels (px)The pixel (px) is the foundation of absolute digital layouts.Definition: Historically tied to single physical device screen dots, CSS defines $1\text{px}$ strictly as $1/96\text{ th of an inch}$.Behavior: Sizing properties specified in px do not stretch or alter automatically when a user resizes their screen or updates device browser font preferences.Best Practice: Use pixels for micromeasurements that require fixed sizing precision, such as thin decorative boundaries (border: 1px solid black;). Avoid pixels for global typography layouts because they break usability and accessibility requirements.3. Container Relative Sizing: Percentages (%)Percentages calculate sizing bounds dynamically based on the current dimensions of an element's immediate parent wrapper box.  CSS.parent-container { width: 500px; }
.child-box { width: 50%; } /* Sizing computes directly to 250px */
Width Mapping: width: 50%; tells the element to stretch across exactly half of the available horizontal area defined by its parent block.Typography Pitfall: When used on font-size, percentages scale based on the parent's current font scale. This can cause text sizes to compound unpredictably in deeply nested layout blocks.4. Viewport Relative Sizing: vw and vhViewport units calculate dimension ratios dynamically from the absolute digital window bounds of the browser screen layout.vw (Viewport Width): One unit scales to exactly $1\%$ of the total viewport width. Setting width: 100vw; forces an element to fill the browser window horizontally.vh (Viewport Height): One unit scales to exactly $1\%$ of the total viewport height. Setting height: 100vh; creates a full-screen block that perfectly matches the viewport window vertically.5. Typography Relative Sizing: em vs. remThese relative metrics calculate scale values dynamically based on font-size configuration bounds.A. The em UnitSizing Reference: Scales relative to the font-size of its immediate parent element.The Compounding Trap: If a parent div has a font-size: 16px;, then 1em inside it equals 16px, and 2em equals 32px. If you nest multiple elements using em, the sizing math compounds exponentially, making maintenance very difficult.CSS.parent { font-size: 2em; } /* Parent scales text up */
.child  { font-size: 2em; } /* Child compounds size further */
B. The rem Unit (Root em)Sizing Reference: Scales relative to the font-size of the root <html> element.Consistency: Because rem bypasses intermediate parental steps to look directly at the root document node, it remains completely consistent anywhere on your webpage.The Default Scale: By default, standard desktop web browsers set their root font-size baseline to exactly 16px. Therefore, unless overridden:$$1\text{rem} = 16\text{px}$$$$1.5\text{rem} = 24\text{px}$$$$2\text{rem} = 32\text{px}$$Core Summary TableUnit TypeClassificationBaseline Reference PointBest Applied To...pxAbsolute$1/96\text{ th}$ of a digital inchBorders, strict hardware alignments%RelativeImmediate Parent Box size propertiesResponsive row widths, padding stepsvwRelative$1\%$ of Browser Viewport Window WidthFluid typography, screen grid boundsvhRelative$1\%$ of Browser Viewport Window HeightHero page barriers, splash screen cardsemRelativeFont-size value of immediate Parent elementSpacing tied contextually to specific text stringsremRelativeFont-size value of root <html> elementGlobal typography layout grids, site padding